If any downstream stage modifies a restricted module or discovers that a restricted module must be modified, that stage must stop and return to PM or Architect review for scope revision. It must not continue under this docs-only architecture.

## Development Guidance

Developer agents must not write product code for this feature.

Before any documentation work, Developer Agents should inspect workspace state and identify touched files. The expected touched files are documentation artifacts only.

Suggested evidence commands:

```bash
git status --short --branch
git diff --stat
git diff --check
```

Ruff, py_compile, and pytest are not required when only Markdown documentation changes are made. If a downstream stage chooses not to run Python checks, the dev or test report must state that they were not run because no Python source or tests were changed.

If any non-documentation file is changed, downstream agents must explain why. If the changed file is production code, trading-sensitive code, runtime configuration, secrets, or generated runtime state, the phase should be rejected unless the task has been formally rescoped.

Development reports must include:

- Requirement document path
- Architecture document path
- Changed files
- Confirmation that changes are documentation-only
- Exact commands and results for commands run
- Skipped commands with reasons
- Remaining risks
- Confirmation that risk, stock-pool filtering, human confirmation, execution policy, data fail-closed behavior, and LLM boundaries were not changed
- Path-format mismatch note where applicable

Test reports must include:

- Requirement, architecture, and development report paths
- Test environment
- Scope and out-of-scope items
- Requirement coverage matrix
- Commands and results
- Defect list
- Feedback bug paths if feedback generation is in scope
- Remaining risk
- Final result: `PASS`, `PASS_WITH_NOTES`, or `REJECTED`

Minimum requirement coverage matrix:

| Requirement Area | Validation Method | Expected Result |
|---|---|---|
| PM requirements exists | Documentation inspection | Required requirements document is present or provided in handoff |
| Architecture exists | Documentation inspection | Architecture document preserves docs-only scope |
| Docs-only scope | Git diff and report inspection | Only documentation files changed |
| Path consistency | Compare PM path and automation metadata | Mismatch is documented as a note |
| Stage-status evidence | Report inspection | Reports identify current stage and required docs |
| Trading-sensitive code unchanged | Git diff inspection | No restricted module changes |
| No product readiness claim | Report and acceptance inspection | Smoke validates pipeline only |
| Safety constraints preserved | Report inspection | No risk, execution, stock-pool, data, strategy, or LLM boundary changes |

Handoff guidance:

- Claude Team A should create a phase plan that keeps all work documentation-only.
- Claude Team B should produce development evidence without editing product modules.
- Claude Team C should verify documentation completeness, path consistency, and absence of trading-sensitive changes.
- Codex review should treat undocumented path mismatches, product-code edits, or product-readiness claims as defects.
- PM acceptance should accept only the automation smoke outcome, not any product feature delivery.

Completion criteria for this architecture stage:

- The architecture document contains the required sections in order.
- The document references the PM requirements.
- The document preserves docs-only scope.
- The document includes module boundaries, phase slices, technical decisions, pseudocode, test strategy, and handoff guidance for Claude Team A/B/C.
- The document explicitly records the path-format inconsistency handling rule.
- The document does not define or imply any production trading behavior.
